firm.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"eea8600c1643bbed\">>>","published":"July 28, 2025","siteName":"www.staffingindustry.com"},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"32b9850410be4355\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nHealthcare Staffing Agencies Are Printing Money Despite (Or Because Of) the Nursing Shortage | The Daily Hire\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"32b9850410be4355\">>>","url":"https://thedailyhire.com/news/healthcare-staffing-agency-boom-2025-12-10","description":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"a7cbb3fa8b9d5f9b\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nAccording to financial disclosures from major agencies, <strong>gross margins on travel nursing placements are running 38-42%</strong>, up from historical averages of 25-30%. When you&#x27;re placing thousands of nurses per quarter and each placement generates tens ...\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"a7cbb3fa8b9d5f9b\">>>","published":"December 10, 2025","siteName":"thedailyhire.com"},{"title":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"05f8f4fb635975b7\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nHow Profitable is a Staffing Agency (2024 Stats)?\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"05f8f4fb635975b7\">>>","url":"https://sharpsheets.io/blog/how-profitable-is-a-staffing-agency/","description":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"6e2289cf1e5d8786\">>>\nSource: Web Search\n---\nA staffing agency has a <strong>~10% operating profit margin</strong> (EBITDA margin) after operating costs (salaries, admin expenses, etc.) have been incurred. Indeed, there are various recurring costs involved in running a staffing agency. The major expenses included the cost of services followed by other ...\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"6e2289cf1e5d8786\">>>","siteName":"sharpsheets.io"}]},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775582965150}}
{"type":"message","id":"dc521c03","parentId":"ee023972","timestamp":"2026-04-07T17:29:44.654Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Got enough. Here's your deep research prompt:\n\n---\n\n**Deep Research Prompt — Healthcare Staffing Agency Financials (for Nava Post 2)**\n\n---\n\nYou are a financial analyst producing a research brief for a healthcare content team. The goal: find verifiable financial data about US healthcare staffing agencies — disclosed in public filings, earnings calls, and industry reports — that proves the structural markup model and why it benefits agencies at facilities' expense.\n\n**Sources to prioritise:**\n- SEC 10-K and 10-Q filings for publicly traded staffing firms (AMN Healthcare, Cross Country Healthcare, CHG Healthcare, Prestige Staffing, Aya Healthcare)\n- Earnings call transcripts (Q3/Q4 2023, Q1-Q4 2024) — seek *exact language* from execs on pricing, margins, and nurse supply\n- SIA (Staffing Industry Analysts) annual market reports and largest-firms rankings\n- Kaufmann Hall hospital profitability reports (they track contract labor reduction and margin impact)\n- State legislative filings on rate-cap bills (California AB / 11 states)\n\n**What to surface:**\n- Revenue, gross margin, and EBITDA margin data per firm, year-on-year\n- The bill rate vs. nurse pay spread — the actual markup disclosed or derivable from filings\n- Any language where agency execs explicitly connect nurse shortage severity to pricing power or margin expansion\n- Operating margin trends for travel/staffing segments specifically (not blended across all business lines)\n- Market concentration data — how much of the $47B market the top 5 firms control\n- State rate-cap legislation results — actual rate data pre/post cap implementation\n\n**What to avoid:**\n- Industry associations or agency-funded research as primary sources\n- Vague references to \"industry data\" without naming the source\n- Any claims that can't be traced to a named document\n\n**Format:**\nStructure as a Statement of Trade — factual, source-backed, organised for easy extraction of individual statistics. Flag clearly where data is thin, contested, or behind a paywall. Note any discrepancies between what agencies say publicly vs. what their filings show.\n\n---\n\nWant me to run this through Gemini deep research now, or do you want to adjust scope first?"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":47404,"output":641,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":48045,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775582984652}}
{"type":"message","id":"d2b31135","parentId":"dc521c03","timestamp":"2026-04-07T17:35:24.835Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-04-07 19:35 GMT+2] This is good but I think we should include hospital chains or LTC or even government facilities if we can. We could discover things that support our cause, hard facts. What do you think?"}],"timestamp":1775583324826}}
{"type":"message","id":"2e8f37af","parentId":"d2b31135","timestamp":"2026-04-07T17:35:55.356Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"That's the right instinct. Here's the full picture of what we can pull and what it would show:\n\n**Hospital chains (publicly traded — searchable 10-Ks):**\n- HCA Healthcare (180+ hospitals), Tenet Healthcare, CommonSpirit — all file 10-Ks. HCA's contract labor line is separately disclosed. If they've been cutting agency spend and margins improved, that's *direct evidence* that the model works. Kaufmann Hall already flagged that 60% of US hospitals increased profits in 2024 partly by reducing contract labor — that's your smoking gun in a suit.\n\n**LTC chains:**\n- CMS (Medicare/Medicaid) requires every Medicare-certified facility to file cost reports annually. These are public records. They disclose: agency nurse spend per facility, total staffing costs, revenue per patient day, overtime. PE-owned chains like Brookdale, Genesis — some file 10-Ks, others are private. The CMS cost reports for the public ones are the real prize: one facility's cost report showing $2.3M in agency markup in a single year is more convincing than any industry average.\n\n**Government facilities:**\n- VA hospitals, county hospitals — budget documents, GAO reports, public records. The VA has been publishing its own nursing shortage data and workforce reports for years. If any have moved to reduce agency spend, there's documentation.\n\n**The chain of proof this builds:**\n1. Agency filings → they make 38-42% gross margins on travel nursing\n2. Hospital 10-Ks → contract labor reduction → margin improvement\n3. CMS cost reports → facility-level agency spend, real dollar amounts\n4. Government data → the human cost of the shortage is documented; the financial fix is documented\n\nThat chain turns \"agencies charge x\" into \"here is the system, here is what it costs you, here is the proof that cutting it works.\" Facilities trust their own financial statements and government data over anything an agency says.\n\nWant me to revise the prompt to include all three tiers, or do you want to narrow the focus?"}],"stopReason":"stop","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":47970,"output":840,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":48810,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775583355354}}
