{"type":"message","id":"9943e473","parentId":"c0d2a99f","timestamp":"2026-04-07T21:32:36.787Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_e1717bcd-4561-4ef8-bfb8-917123296e2b","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace && python3 tinyqe/tinyqe.py --format json << 'EOF'\nIn Q4 2024, AMN Healthcare reported $62 million in what they called \"labor disruption revenue\" — $22 million over their own guidance. The CEO called it a revenue stream, and she wasn't embarrassed. Here's what that word \"disruption\" actually means — and who pays for it.\n\n\"Labor disruption\" is AMN's product name. Hospitals pay the bill rate. Nurses get a fraction of it. AMN keeps the spread. California's contract nursing hit $116/hour in 2023, up from $81 in 2019. That $35 gap didn't go to nurses. It went to margins. AMN runs a 30.8% gross margin and 11.4% EBITDA margin. The model is working exactly as designed.\n\nHere's the verdict: this is not a market failure. It is a market operating precisely as the agencies built it. The signal is in the behavior of the hospitals themselves — UHS, HCA, and Tenet are all actively reducing contract labor exposure. When the customer starts running, you have to ask: is this a broken model, or a model that was never meant to work for you?\nEOF","timeout":30}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":45503,"output":330,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":45833,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1775597556787}}
